The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Mumbai, Sept. 24: India?s foreign exchange (forex) reserves fell by $3.7 billion during the week ended September 16 to stand at $144.222 billion, according to the Reserve Bank of India. Foreign currency assets also decreased by $1.047 billion to stand at $138.243 billion. The fall is prim-arily due to revaluation of non-US foreign currencies such as euro, sterling and yen, analysts said.

 Washington, Sept. 24: The financial sector of the country would be opened up further, but this would happen gradually after putting in place appropriate laws and appointing regulators, finance minister P. Chidambaram said. ?Our intention is to move forward, but at every step the watchword will be caution and placing suitable instruments to prevent financial shocks,? Chidambaram said in his lecture at Yale University.

 New Delhi, Sept. 24: ONGC Videsh Limited (OVL) has paid its maiden dividend of Rs 105 crore for 2004-05 to its parent Oil and Natural Gas Corp (ONGC). The dividend works out to Rs 35 per share of Rs 100 each on three crore shares.




